segments.text: Okay, we're talking to Mr. Ole Cassini.
You said that book had to be written, sir.
Yes, because, first of all, the people have a very one-dimensional idea about Jackie.
The book had to be written because it's part of history.
This is a lady that single-handedly created Camelot.
This is a lady that was inspired, being a Francophile,
by Versailles.
She thought she would create the ambiance, the beauty, the interesting people, all of which were part of the ancient French courts.
And she was erudite, she was interested, and she was ambitious.
So, step by step, surrounding herself with the people she considered the best qualified for the job,
She began phase two of her life, because I see Jackie in four phases.
Really?
She was four ladies, not one.
She was a complex personality.
And where I thought that I had to do something is because I thought that unless a beautiful book was put together, that...
wonderful achievement that she got in creating camera art would not be clearly understood.

I think this graphically shows with the modest talent that I have as a writer, but having enough culture and interest, I thought that I would put a book together that would be a permanent part of America.
It may seem ambitious,

It may seem for me to be ambitious about this project, but I thought that if you could have a non-polemic book beautifully presented, step by step showing how she gained confidence in her job, how she became really the first lady of the land, and one of the most important characters in recent history.
Did she know that you were working on this before she died?
No.
She did not know.
I didn't know I was going to do it.
You probably would not have done it, do you think, if she were still alive?
I would have stopped because there were two things that were interesting in the book.
First, I wanted to put to the best of my ability together this thousand days of magic that were magical for the nation, for the world, and for me.
And then, secondly, I wanted to redress certain of the things
that I went through 35 years, because if she'd been alive, she was always there to defend me.
She was a very, very private person.
She didn't want people to interfere.
Very loyal, it sounds.
But very, very loyal.
So she...
It was important for me to put the letters that she wrote me.
Of course, the letters are letters that are interesting only because they refer to the work I was doing for her.
But in the casting, at the beginning, a lot of people in the industry didn't want to acknowledge that I had the right to be considered.
I just didn't fit.
Why do you suppose that is?
Well, I don't know.
For the very reason that I fitted with them, somehow, for some of the cogniscenti of the 7th Avenue, they proposed other designers.
It was a very plum job.
It was an important thing for me, for any designer.
And the traditional viewpoint in fashion was that you have to go to Paris first.
and then pay homage there, and then come back, and then pretend that you're creative, when in effect, often, you just copy what they do.
I think a point you make is that this was an American statement, too.
Yes.
And that's very important, isn't it?
Yes.
And it's a very good question, because the key was that I created a look for her.
I didn't want to create dresses for the sake of creating dresses.
I want to be logical.
And that's why she selected me, because in Hollywood I had the opportunity to work with a script.
In effect, I was given a script.
That's wonderful.
I love that whole concept.
I was given a script, and it was easy for me, because I had worked in Italy, I had worked in France, I had worked in Hollywood, and on Seventh Avenue, so I had a pretty good record there.
The question was,
Why me?
Why me is because I was more than a designer.
I was a friend of the family, trusted, because above all, there was a question of trust.
And, of course, because she thought that my international experience and my being an American and my military service... But also your royal...
Blood must have been helpful too, I would think.
Well, in her viewpoint, yes, because she thought that I would be able to interpret a look for her that was for her role.
She always said to me, you dressed me for the role.
She said that.
Yes.
She said that to me and to others.
So you don't think it was ego then?
No, I think that once she got some competence, because it was like a play in Broadway.
And she was young, too.
I think people forget how young she was.
Very young, and suddenly thrust into a position of such power where every movement was analyzed.
She became a number one ambassador in the world.
But power is a strange...

strange thing it affects people differently and as she grew in power she realized that she really had something that she could do a mission you you recount in the book how when you went to see her in the hospital and she said she immediately asked you if you'd work with work with her and you said only if I do it alone correct I thought that was a very gutsy thing for you to do it was gutsy it was I recognized this it was a
Take your chance and say the thing you should say.
Because I said to her, and I think you read it before, I said, look, if you have more than one person, you're going to have tremendous battles for recognition from all your designers.
And discretion will not be a part of their everyday diet because they're going to fight for recognition.
And you would spend a lot of time with them.
You need somebody, and it doesn't have to be me, because I was a friend after all.
She said, take someone that will see what they have to do, do it for you diligently, and then you'll be much more comfortable.
And then at that time, she said, but you know, I already ordered a dress and bird clothes.
I read that.
It's wonderful.
And I said, I understand that.
So she called Bergdorf, and you read that, and she said, Cassini will do the designing.
And you can make it.
And you can make them.
And they said, no, we have designers.
So it didn't work out to a person.
That wasn't too smart of them, was it?
I think it was not smart at all.
Because at least they would have gotten some recognition out of it.
Continuous recognition.
Yeah.
So you made the...
all of this material in your shop.
Well, I was a very successful designer at the time, and I consider myself successful today.
I was one of the best lines on 7th Avenue, and I created a separate entity to be able to service her.
I was amazed that there were 300 outfits for 1,000 days.
That's one every three days.
Yes, but a lot of designs were not even photographed.
I mean, that's a lot of work for you.
Tremendous.
Tremendous.
When I look at that book, sometimes I take that book and I look at it.
And I said, how could you do it?
It was so, there were many risks.
First of all, what really happened, it was very lucky for me, is that the first two or three outfits that appeared were saluted by everybody as being wonderful.
And the most severe critics of fashion are the French.
And they recognized that a new look had been born and that there was a tranquil, dignified look for a first lady.
I wasn't trying to use her as a model for my collection and my ideas.
I was just going with the scenario.
Was there anything that you did for her that she didn't like?
A couple of times.
Did she ever send things back?
She sent me a couple things back.
Did you learn from these?
I learned from them because I had an idea that because she was an equestrian and a very good one.
And you were an instructor in the cavalry.
Yeah, I was also doing the same things with horses and we had a horse dialogue going.
And I sent her a quote that I recreated.
It was kind of inspired by the hunt, the pink.
Okay.
And I thought that she would love it.
Unfortunately, I picked the regular fabric that is used for such things and turned out to be so heavy that she couldn't wear it.
So she sent it back and she said, very good idea, but it's too heavy.
I can't wear it.
What did she, what kind of input did she, did she give input?
Did she help her?
Only very general.
Look,
If you look at, when she hired the cook for the White House because she wanted French cuisine, she would say to the cook, prepare me a menu and do it.
And the same with me.
Once I presented the sketches and she liked them, and 99% of the time she liked them, she said, do it.
Just do it.
So you presented her with sketches first.
Yes.
But people had the idea, completely erroneous, that she arrived at the White House from phase one to phase two with a lot of clothes, wheat-torn luggage, having lived in luxury and all that.
No, it was not.
She was very parsimonious in the first phase.
First she'd been a reporter and then married to a senator.
Jack Kennedy didn't spend much on clothes.
He was such a charismatic, elegant figure.
He didn't need it.
But she needed it.
And she'd say, all right, I'm going to India.
What do you think?
So I had to think about the colors, the fabrics, because of the climate.
So I had to put the thing in work.
And in the letters you will see that she was very kind towards me.
She constantly complimented me and kept my morale high.
And I did my job.
I kept doing my job.
Canada is one thing.
Climate is one thing.
India is another thing.
France is another thing.
England is another thing.
Not just these countries, but we're talking about the Pope and De Gaulle.
Yes.
They wanted to interview me about the dress she wore when she visited the Pope.
But I could not do the interview because we had made a deal with CBS, with...
Good Morning America, which was postponed because of O.J.
Simpson.
So I find myself squeezed in between O.J.
Simpson and the Pope.
Quite a country, isn't it?
It is a country.
It is.
I love your observation that what you developed for her was a concept.
I wonder if you could just talk a little bit about this conceptual... Well, first of all, I remember having real fear when suddenly she said, you're the one.
I said, what do I do now?
Because it was easy to talk, but to do it was another thing.
And I said, go back to your background.
See what you can learn from your background to do a good job here.
And I felt suddenly...
completely relaxed when I said, I'm going to do what I did in Hollywood.
I'm going to think about her life, what she's going to have to do, I want to facilitate her life.
Everything has to be perfect because she was such a perfectionist, believe me.
Friends or no friends, if I had not done the job in the first two weeks, I was a goner.
Oh, I'm sure of that.
A goner.
And I knew it.
People at that level don't call high power.
No.
And the strange thing about power, because in my life I've been very lucky, I've been close to high power.
And they change.
They change.
No matter.
It's not pejoratively said, it's just that when you constantly, constantly, sycophantically change,
treated during night and day, it is impossible in human nature not to take some of it.
So she really was a taskmaster.
She wanted the best, and she thought she got the best, and I thought she got the best.
Let's say that she's the same person, with the same temperament, with the same aspirations, and that she looks a little different.
I'm not saying that she's unattractive, but was it necessary for her to be the woman that she was physically for you to create?
Yes, because
Another very good question, because there are limitations.
There were no limitations with her.
She was a pretty woman.
The question was to make her appear as pretty as possible, because every human body has some things that are better than other features, you know.
And so I made a profound anatomical analysis of her.
I also said to myself, where does the inspiration come?
What is she to you?
All right, she's the first lady now.
You have to satisfy every whim.
But who is she for you?
To me, she was an ancient princess of Egypt.
The wife of a pharaoh, maybe, because her lines were very geometric.
You give her measurements in here, too.
Yes, it's interesting.
And so this inspiration...
was logical because I knew that she would wear certain clothes extremely well.
Other things would not be suited for her.
If suddenly I decided to aggrandize my own name, to dress her in frilly things, no, there had to be a draconian departure.
Eliminate everything and start from scratch for her.
Don't have preconceived notions.
Only do things that will make her appear at her best.

First example, when I realized that she was going to be seen by the world during the swearing-in, it was a very cold day, I remember, in January, I believe, and I had been given the instruction that she needed something.
At that point, she didn't even have the time to tell me what she would like, the color she would like.
So I said to my, I looked,
I tried to look at the scene.
I said, well, all these ladies are going to wear fur coats.
And they look like bears.
Now I'm going to have her look like a young, beautiful, simple thing.
And that little coat, base coat, with pillbox, by the way, that other people said they're designed, which is not true, uh...
made her look so young, so fresh, so pretty, so unpretentious.
Because one of the things that I think I was lucky to get into right away, that although she was regal in her periods, there was some quiet elegance, laissez faire, like if it was a natural thing.
It was not some effort to create it.
clothes that everybody would say, oh, how wonderful that dress.
I want people to say how wonderful she looked.
Focus on her beauty.
How often did you have to go to Washington?
Oh, all the time.
All the time.
And there, of course, I had the advantage of being invited to dinner, stayed there, come in any time.
I mean, you know.
Pretty nice.
But I have to tell you a little thing that happened to me.
The first group of dresses that after two weeks where she stayed in,
and she had nothing to wear, truly nothing to wear, I told the secretary that I would arrive with some clothes.
And I took the train, and I had about eight or nine boxes, big boxes like that.
I couldn't find a porter, and I expected the White House to send somebody to help me.
And I looked around, and it was snowing at Castle Road.
Well, I want to tell you something, that there was a snafu, and nobody came to pick me up.
So I had to be in line, pushing these boxes on my seat, while there were hundreds of people asking for a taxi.
Finally, slipping a 20 to the guy, I got myself a place in a cab with five other people.
Wow.
And he said, where are we going?
I said, the White House.
So we go to the White House.
They clear me, and they say, Cassini and his
as people are coming in, and they thought the passengers were my people.
I was alone.
And these people were absolutely amazed.
I'm sure they still talk about that to this very day.
I guess, have we regressed since then?
Because it was such a statement of fashion and how important things are.
I'm just thinking in terms of
How important was she as a leader, as a senator?
Well, she was important then, but the more interesting thing, by coincidence, in history, every major designer is doing the Jackie Look now.
Still?
I still have a return to it.
No, the return, why?
Good question.
I gave it a lot of thought, believe me.
We are a country that is not at ease.
We are very, very
We're passing a strange period in our history, in the world, as a matter of fact.
So the designers for years now have done clothes not for people but for the media.
So they would pick a genetically perfect individual, put some crazy clothes on them, parade them, and these were wearable clothes.
And suddenly, because they didn't sell in the stores and because
There was a nostalgic desire to go to a quieter elegance.
Who could, better than her, could give that example?
So today, everybody, I reproduce the entire line that I did for her, and every store is buying it.
I understand you're bringing out a line, is it this fall, the black tie line?
Well, the black tie is done all along, but in the black tie, there is a group.
I mean, there was some Jackie inspired.
Yeah, oh yeah, yeah.
And that's coming out?
It's now.
It's in the store.
Because I read the presses of this flaw.
I guess this is the flaw.
Yeah.
Tell me about some of these ingenious things, like the hat and the... Where did that come from?
Well, that little pillbox.
The pillbox.
The pillbox was born this way.
In my inspiration, I thought about Egypt.
And if you really think of what... Nefertiti.
Nefertiti.
Exactly.
Nefertiti, I said.
Furthermore, she didn't particularly like hands.
So I had to create non-hands.
Something that would finish the whole look, but was not...
Again focusing on the hat itself.
Was the muff your idea too?
The thing she put her hand in?
Yes, yes.
It was called a muff, I think.
Yes.
But she, I didn't do that for her.
She had, she got it from one of her relatives.
And because I'm a nun for designer, even the little mink that she put around her collar, that was hers.
And it finished the outfit very nicely, but I mean it.
Now I had a terrible experience when I recommended to her to
wear a, because it was out of fashion at the time, a leopard coat.
And I still feel the pain of having done that, because they almost killed all the leopards in the world.
They became so fashionable.
And that turned me away from all of that, and I am now regretted.
It's one of the sins, involuntary sins, I committed.
We weren't, don't we?
No.
You...
Of course, now you've made clothes for Grace Kelly.
What if Grace Kelly had been the first lady?
Same thing.
It would have been the same.
She was almost the first lady.
I understand.
She is a... She would have played... She would have been dressed differently, but she would have been a very good first lady, Grace Kelly.
I'm also talking about how would you...

had the same assignment let's say to if Grace had been the first lady and you had had the same position with her that you had with Jackie do you think you would have done similar kinds of no because the bodies were different I would have done completely in fact I think I'm going to do a collection on Grace Kelly a completely different approach so obviously the
physical, the body, as you say.
The body.
She had a long neck.
She had a sphinx-like interesting face.
An exquisite woman.
Yes.
And everything lended itself to the hieroglyphical kind of inspiration.
No frills in all her clothes.
Very great simplicity.
We're talking about Kelly now, right?
No, we're talking about... Grace would have been another thing.
More diaphanous, more...
Angelic, a different type.
But you say in the book you imagined the use for the particular dress, the outfit.
So let's say that you were imagining the same event, meeting with the Pope, meeting with de Gaulle.
It would still have been different.
It would have been different, yeah.
Completely different.
Interesting.
Did you wear many of these things over again?
Yes, many.
I think our misconception is that she wore one of these dresses once.
No, no, no.
Some of the more recognizable dresses she wore two or three times.
She liked them.
Publicly?
Publicly.
And she had them made in different colors.
She did, yes.
I love the fact that she had said that you reproduced it in the book.
Under no circumstances she absolutely has to have the first.
Yes.
Why was that so important?
Well,
It would have been commercial otherwise.
It would have been seen that I was profiting from that to put in my collection.
In fact, I never, never, never put any of the dresses that I did for her in my collection.
Really?
Never.
Never?
Never.
Because the American woman I was thinking about for my collection was not the first lady of the land.
It was a completely different thing and the people don't understand
A painter like Picasso had periods in his life.
He had the blue period and all kinds of different moments in the evolution of a talent.
And without comparing myself to a great master like Picasso, I think I am, in a commercial art like fashion, I am one of the best.
And I can imagine certain things because a good designer has to have a sense of history,
has to have a political sense, has to have what the consumer is concerned about, what it needs.
So you have to be... Would you say that your experience with her, I mean, very successful, noted, famous...
designer before your collaboration with her.
I don't even know if you consider it a collaboration.
You did work for her.
Of course, you've done remarkable things since.
But would you say, nevertheless, that that was more or less the defining event?
Yes, because here I was dealing with a lady that was admired worldwide.
Every work, every dress that I would do, coat or suit, whatever,
were scrutinized by the world.
Thousands and thousands, hundreds of thousands of women imitated her.
So I think one thing we never address, or that I've not heard addressed, is this is risky.
It's an opportunity of a lifetime, but it was fraught with some risks for you, I would think.
A Broadway play.
You don't know how it's going to go, first night.
You're putting a lot of money behind it, lots of hopes, and suddenly, showtime.
So, I mean, this could have, it did wonderful things for your reputation, it certainly only enhanced it, but worst case scenario is... Worst case scenario, I would have been obliterated.
Really?
Were you alert to that possibility?
Well, fortuna, you were audacious.
Good luck follows the audacious.
I mean, you know, in life you have moments where enough, you have the vision of what could happen, good and bad, and you have to take a chance if you want to go forward.
If you want to be safe, that's not the game you want to play.
That's not a safe game.
She certainly is unique to our lifetimes, isn't she?
Yes.
I don't know how many First Ladies there have been since then, and I certainly, even outside of the White House, I can't think of another woman.
Well, you won't have anything.
The combination of certain factors.
A handsome president, rich, photogenic and charismatic, a First Lady of great beauty, dignity, and good taste.
Intelligence.
Intelligence and education.
Let's not forget the education.
Your brother called her, named her debutante of the year.
The year.
How?
How could those many factors converge again?
Never.
It will never be again.
Really?
Never.
It cannot.
There is a, you know, you had some...
They were young, good-looking, rich.
They had everything.
They were the dream of everybody.
Amazing, isn't it?
Amazing.
To have lived through that.
Yes.
Was Camelot her conception?
Yes.
It came after a trip to Canada because the defining moment was after the enormous success she had when she visited Canada, the president looked at her differently.
There was not only the wife he loved, but a tremendous political attu, Trump card, I mean.
He suddenly realized, and he said it later when he was in France, I'm the guy that came, I'm paraphrasing, with Jackie Kennedy.
But suddenly she became a political tool of the first order.
Asset.
Asset.
I guess is the word, the operative word they used.
Asset.
Big asset.
And he recognized it when he went to France and he said to himself, he said, I'm the man who's with Mrs. Kennedy.
And the French were bananas over there, didn't they?
It was quite an experience for you, I guess.
Fantastic.
And there could have been the case, because the French was silly and their criticism.
There was nothing but only compliments from the French press and from the people at large.
They liked the way she looked.
She looked like the first lady.
I'm just looking at my notes here if there's anything up.
Pardon me for jumping around.
No, no, go ahead.
Do you want something to drink?
No, I'm fine.
Thank you, sir.
I've been invited to your reception tonight, but I think I'm going to take a train back.
I came down from Massachusetts.
You're welcome, but whatever.
I'd love to, at some point, I've recently written a book of my own, which is doing pretty well.
In fact, Rizzoli has it.
It's on collecting, on bibliomania, and I understand that you're quite a collector of things.
I am collecting certain things.
And armor, and I noticed this.
Look at this paneling.
I'll bet you this is something.
How old is this?
This house was brought in by the Wells Fargo family.
Oh, really?
It's a 17th century Dutch house on the exterior.
And the paneling is Italian and English, 15th, 16th century.

And the armor that I have downstairs, afterwards you might want to give a look through it, is all things I collected from the various... Eva Kasten in England, Lord Astor, I bought an armor from... Here and there, I collect something like that, and I think this goes well...
With my upbringing, after all, I was brought up in Florence, a medieval city, small medieval city.
And when I'm in this house, I feel at home.
I had to recreate the ambiance.
Why armor?
I understand that you actually have said that armor made a fashion statement in its own way.
Absolutely, in its own way.
But armor because in my own, had the world not changed when I was a kid,
A child.
Had we not lost everything, chances are there never would be a designer.
That would never be my first choice.
I thought the army, to be part of the guards, and that was a cavalry officer.
That was my thing.
And today I'm still that way.
I'm a professional driver.
I race with my own horses.
I do the things that, in my heart of hearts,
would have been my first selection.
Armour too, that comes to the... I mean, it's atavistic almost.
You look wonderful, by the way.
Do you exercise?
You must exercise all the time.
Yeah, I've been in violent sports, and I'm 82 years old, but my doctor tells me, keep doing what you're doing because you're out of the ordinary.
You're really in marvelous shape.
I believe...
if it interests you at all, I mean that we don't use our imagination and our minds sufficiently.
I think you can slow down disease.
I think you can increase your life span.
I think you can almost fit to your desire your body.
I mean, I'm vain because it's been good for me to be vain.
I look at myself and say, come on, you're getting a little fat here.
I have a special pair of jeans that I put on.
If I see that I'm gaining a little weight, I just sacrifice and I eliminate certain things because I feel that I have to have the physical part of the role.
I mean, I am a creator, and I have to look like a creator.
Can you, just to jump around a little bit, can you compare the...
The White House, you said the four phases, and you do have them in the book too, but I guess you kind of lost touch with Jackie after the assassination.
Well, first thing, first of all, I gave a party in this very house for her in Onassis when they got married.
And I knew Onassis a long time before she ever knew him.
And it was, as a matter of fact, one of the few defenders of her marriage at that time
They were really furious at Jackie.
They wanted her to be a vestal virgin and remain up there somewhere, untouchable.
She went to Europe, but when you have your husband killed, when you have his brother killed, when this happens, you're suddenly worried about the future.
It's very understandable that she left.
She left.
It was too much.
She held on with great dignity to the tragic moment.
But after that, she wanted peace and quiet and money and yachts.
Security.
Security for the children, too.
I wrote a little blurb about her in my book because my book is about the passion for books.
It's over 25 centuries.
And when she died, her son came out and said she was with her friends, her family.
She was surrounded by her friends, her family, and her book.
Remember that quotation?
Yes, yes.
She went home to be with her books, her family, and her friends.
I thought that was quite a very poignant statement.
I agree with you.
I think she accelerated her own demise because she didn't want to look the way she looked.
Perfectionist to the end.
She wanted to go.
It was time to go.
You believe this in your heart?
I believe in my heart.
Because?
Would you just say that again?
Do you think because she wasn't exactly the way?
She didn't want to deal with the deterioration of the body.
And I know a doctor that told me because she was taking care of it.
She said, all right, I'm going home.
And she ended it up because I believe that the mind can do it.
I think you can absolutely...
desire to die.
I believe that.
And she did it.
Why is it so often you see a husband dies and the wife dies?
Right away after.
Or vice versa.
It happens so often.
So often.
So often.
We can kill ourselves easily.
Or my father, who's 84, you know, he works, he has his own little business, and he goes in every day.
And we say, why?
It's not making any money.
It doesn't matter.
No.
He goes in, and he's
This is his little empire, you know, and it keeps him alive.
If we close that thing, he dies.
And I think that's exactly what you're saying.

Well, in my case, I hope I have enough resiliency intellectually to, if I lost my business, etc., I would still want to die because it's a short experience anyway, life, and you want to go through it in as elegant a way as you can.
What was the ultimate satisfaction for you, knowing that you had participated, would you consider this an historic event?
Absolutely.
Certainly in the history of fashion, and you might even just talk generally about fashion.
Yes, I mean, it was a great accomplishment.
It is proven to be one, because 35 years later, it's just the same interest.
Among people who weren't even alive then.
That's right.
Young women, 35, 25, were wearing these clothes.
Absolutely.
I went to the Nixon Library the other day.
I just came back from California.
And I signed for 850 books there.
Really?
And I had to go there.
There were maybe a hundred more people there that I could have signed books for.
So I mean, that she is a goddess in the minds of people, no doubt.
Larger than life, to use the cliche.
Yes, larger than life.
And you clothed her?
